     * News in Brief: Bats are 3-D cartographers
       Special cells in the mammal's brain chart its path as it flies.
     * Infants, whether mice or human, love to be carried
       Being toted around calms and quiets babies of both species.
     * News in Brief: Some like it acidic
       In a higher-carbon world of altered oceans, a shelled plankton species may flourish.
     * News in Brief: Coelacanth is not closest fishy relative of terrestrial animals
       Genes of "living fossil" do reveal changes needed to live on dry land.
     * Dinosaur embryos were restless, speedy growers
       Hundreds of fossils found in China suggest some unhatched dinos kicked their legs.
     * A giant tortoise by any other name
       Long, heated battle ends with a moniker for the Indian Ocean reptile.
     * News in Brief: Termites, not fairies, cause plant circles in African deserts
       Underground insect engineers create water traps in the soil, allowing rings of green grasses in the sand.
     * Blind cave-dwelling fish also hard of hearing
       Two species that live in the dark have worse hearing than do their surface-living cousins.
     * News in Brief: Impending death alters crickets' standards for mates
       With a short time to live, parasite-infested females lose their preference for fast-chirping males.
     * News in Brief: Longhorn cattle ancestors came from Pakistan
       New World breeds trace back to both major bovine lineages, genetic analysis shows.
     * How mammals grow ears: With a flaw
       A newly discovered rupture-and-repair process that occurs in embryos could explain a lot about infections and hearing defects.
     * Disease threatens garden impatiens
       Surprising scientists, once-mild downy mildew has struck the popular blooms in 33 states.
     * Giant squid population is one big happy species
       Elusive deep ocean dwellers have low genetic diversity despite living around the globe.
     * Microbes flourish at deepest ocean site
       At the bottom of the Mariana Trench, eleven kilometers down, bacteria prosper despite crushing pressure and isolation.
     * Shorter-winged swallows evolve around highways
       In survey along Nebraska roads, number of birds killed by cars has plummeted over 30 years.
     * News in Brief: Bedbugs raise genetic defense against pesticides
       Bedbugs turn on several genes, in both their shells and their nerve cells, to stave off effects of insecticides.
     * Tasmanian devil disease reveals its secrets
       The contagious cancer evades the animal's immune system by turning off key genes.
     * Caffeine's buzz attracts bees to flowers
       Nectar of some blooms carries the drug, which improves bee memory.
     * Alga borrows genes to beat the heat, acid and toxic metals
       Such genetic theft from bacteria and archaea is unusual among eukaryotes.
     * Camel ancestors lived in the Arctic
       Fossils on Ellesmere Island suggest famous desert dweller got its start in cold regions.
     * Native pollinators boost crop yields worldwide
       Farms with crops from coffee to mangoes don't get the best yields if they rely solely on honeybees.
     * Impact craters may have been a toasty home for early life
       The heat generated during a cosmic crash could have nurtured ancient organisms.
     * Tadpoles with eyes in their tails see the light
       Transplanted eyes in the creature's tail can distinguish between red and blue.
     * How weaver ants get a grip
       Strong sticking power and quick reaction time help the insects stay put in trees.
     * Bees learn the electric buzz of flowers
       Floral electric fields could join color and fragrance as cues to pollinators.
     * Chill turns monarchs north
       Temperature manipulation appears to solve mystery of what triggers migratory butterflies' homeward trip.
     * Bird, human tweets come from similar parts of the brain
       Genetics study finds parallels in birdsong and language.
     * News in Brief: Melting Arctic may make algae flourish
       More sunlight penetrates thinning Arctic sea ice, enabling algal growth.

